==English==

{{webster 1913}}

===Etymology===
From the {{Gr.}} ''periphrasis''.  Cf. {{F.}} ''[[périphrastique]]''.

===Adjective===
'''periphrastic'''

# expressed in [[more]] [[word|words]] than are [[necessary]]
#:'''1916''' Martin Brown Ruud[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/16416/16416-8.txt] : 
#::''As poetry it does not measure up to Aasen; as translation it is '''periphrastic''', arbitrary, not at all faithful.''
# {{grammar}} characterized by [[periphrase]] \ [[circumlocution]].
#: ''the active '''periphrastic''' conjugation in Latin is formed by using the future active participle and the appropriate form of ''[[esse]]'' 
#: ''"the daughter of the man" may be used as a '''periphrastic''' synonym for "the man's daughter"'' 
# indirect in naming an entity; [[circumlocutory]]
#:'''1870''' Edward Bulwer-Lytton, in ''Vril: The Power of the Coming Race''[http://www.marxists.org/reference/archive/bulwer/1871/coming-race.htm] : 
#::''In writing, they deem it irreverent to express the Supreme Being [... and] in conversation they generally use a '''periphrastic''' epithet, such as the ''All-Good''.''

===See also===
*[[periphrastic conjugation]] {{grammar}} : a conjugation formed by the use of the simple verb with one or more auxiliaries.

